I don't get your argumentation. This is basicly what I have in mind for JNA:

```java
public final class Native implements Version {
    public static final Charset DEFAULT_CHARSET;
    public static final String DEFAULT_ENCODING;
    static {
        String nativeEncoding = System.getProperty("native.encoding");
        Charset nativeCharset = null;
        if(nativeEncoding != null) {
            Charset.forName(nativeEncoding);
        }
        if(nativeCharset == null) {
            nativeCharset = Charset.defaultCharset();
        }
        DEFAULT_CHARSET = nativeCharset;
        DEFAULT_ENCODING = nativeCharset.name();
    }
```

On JDK17 and lower this will be the current behavior (default to file.encoding). On JDK 18 it will pick up the new property and use that. From JNAs point of few nothing changes:

On JDK 17 and lower:
- `native.encoding` is not set
- `Charset.defaultCharset()` matches the native codepage and is used as basis
- JNA will use the correct native codepage

On JDK 18:
- `native.encoding` is set to the native encoding
- `Charset.defaultCharset()` is UTF-8
- JNA would use native.encoding

The end result: Great, nothing changes for JNA.

Now **with your change**:

On JDK 17 and lower:
- `native.encoding` is not set
- `Charset.defaultCharset()` is UTF-8
- the default behavior of JNA changes and will not use the native codepage anymore

On JDK 18:
- `native.encoding` is set
- `Charset.defaultCharset()` is UTF-8
- JNA would use native codepage

Result: JNA is broken/changes behavior on JDK 17 and lower, from JDK 18 the fixed version would be fixed.

JNA can't work around your approach, while the changes in JEP 400 leave an option for a work-around. So from my POV the suggested change here is worse than the change caused by JEP400.

